SPHN-DCC-14	BioMedIT training: Responsible Use of Health-Related Data for Research (2 courses) covering mostly ELSI aspects	{}	\N	Webinar/online training\n\nResponsible use of health-related data for research\nResponsible health data usage\nDeveloped by the Health Ethics and Policy Lab at the ETH Zurich and based on the SPHN Ethical Framework for Responsible Data Processing in Personalized Health Research", this course will allow you to familiarize yourself with the ethical framework along with its key points about responsible usage of health data for research purposes.\nPlease note a SWITCH edu-ID is required to access this course.\n\nLegal agreements in multi-center projects\nDetailed advice how to set up legal agreements when using health-related data in multi-center projects in Switzerland.\nThis training covers the different types of agreements available, and what other legal aspects you need to consider when preparing your multi-center research project.\nFor support, contact the SPHN Data Coordination Center.	\N	{}	{"data collection","data reuse"}	{}	{}	{training}	{https://sphn.ch/training/}	{}	{}	2025-11-14 12:53:18.381	2025-12-11 12:37:53.435	t	SPHN
SPHN-DCC-15	BioMedIT training: Information Security, data protection (5 courses)	{}	\N	Webinar/online training \n\nSPHN/BioMedIT Data Privacy and IT Security Training\nWithin the Swiss Personalized Health Network (SPHN) and related national initiatives researchers use patient data (i.e., confidential human data) in their research projects. Dealing with confidential human data requires awareness of data privacy, respective laws and information security. These courses explain the legal and regulatory context or personalised health research and  what should be done in practice to protect the patients’ privacy when performing biomedical research on human data.\nCompleting the courses is mandatory for users of BioMedIT, and taking this course is highly recommended for all users of SPHN infrastructures.\n    Data Provider Training\n    Data Manager Training\n    Project's Permission Manager Training\n    Research User Training	\N	{}	{"data collection","data reuse"}	{completion,conception,development,execution}	{}	{training}	{https://sphn.ch/training/}	{}	{}	2025-11-14 12:53:18.557	2025-12-11 12:37:53.661	t	SPHN
SPHN-DCC-13	BioMedIT	{}	\N	Secure IT environment (HPC) enabling collaborative processing and analysis of data. End-to-end secure processing ensured from data provider to analysis, IT services and related research support (e.g. data management)\nBioMedIT provides a secure platform for research using sensitive data. It allows for the mobilisation of health data, its processing and exploitation in support of improved clinical practice and new biomedical knowledge.  \nThis platform spans three major Swiss research institutions, which employ modern cloud technology and cutting-edge security procedures. Data from providers such as hospitals and research organizations is encrypted and transferred into the platform, where it can be safely accessed by Swiss researchers or groups from all academic research institutions.\nThe three BioMedIT sites (nodes) form a shared security zone, such that once data is brought into the platform, it can be accessed and processed on any of the nodes. Projects from research consortia or single researchers wishing to use sensitive data are set up as research projects on one of the nodes in a BioMedIT project-specific environment, called a 'B-space'.\nResearch groups can access their B-spaces via the BioMedIT Portal, where they can manage users and encryption keys, initiate data transfers and access support and other tools and services offered by BioMedIT.\nResearchers securely access the system using two factor authentication, and extract only nonsensitive or aggregated research results while leaving the sensitive data in the platform. \nBioMedIT is open to all Swiss universities, research institutes, hospitals, service providers and other interested partners. In addition, and specifically within the framework of the two Swiss national initiatives SPHN and PHRT, the BioMedIT Network can be used for mono- and multi-site, individual and collaborative research projects. BioMedIT is a project of the SIB Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics. \nBioMedIT is an integral part of SPHN and was developed along the needs of SPHN funded projects.	\N	{}	{"data collection","data reuse"}	{completion,execution}	{"ethics submission","project management"}	{consulting,"IT infrastructure"}	{https://www.biomedit.ch/}	{}	{biomedit@sib.swiss}	2025-11-14 12:53:18.202	2025-12-11 12:40:28.827	t	SPHN
SPHN-DCC-19	Metadata service (standards) providing computer-based access to FAIR data points and repositories	{}	\N	Provision of standards allowing data (e.g. on a website) to be readable and accessible by a computer\nThe SPHN Metadata Catalog was developed with the goal of facilitating data discovery and reusability. At its core, it serves as a portal, enabling users to easily explore catalogs and datasets generated by SPHN-funded and SPHN-related projects. It acts as a bridge between projects and data users, supporting exploration of the available qualitative and quantitative metadata. The SPHN Metadata Catalog consists of two key components: SPHN FAIR Data Point (responsible for hosting and displaying rich, qualitative metadata about available catalogs and datasets) and the SPHN Schema Scope (provides an interactive visualization of the data schemas and the associated quantitative metadata of available catalogs and datasets). The SPHN FAIR Data Point (FDP) plays a pivotal role in supporting the SPHN Metadata Catalog. As a key component of this catalog, the FDP enhances data sharing and discovery in biomedical research by hosting detailed metadata about health-related datasets available across multiple institutions. The metadata catalogs within the FDP provide comprehensive overviews of datasets, adhering to the FAIR principles. These catalogs describe the datasets' structure, content, and provenance while ensuring sensitive patient data remains secure. Through its integration into the SPHN Metadata Catalog, the FDP allows researchers to easily discover and identify what data is available and how it can be accessed, simplifying the process of locating relevant datasets while maintaining robust data privacy protocols.\nThe SPHN Schema Scope is available for discovering and exploring the SPHN core dataset and datasets from SPHN-funded projects, allowing to explore individual concepts in the full context of the schema graph. It offers researchers a highly interactive way to visualize data schemas, simplifying the navigation of even the most complex data structures.\nA FAIR Data Point (FDP) is a REST API (Application Programming Interface built according to the design principles of the REST-architecture (Representational State Transfer)) for creating, storing, and serving FAIR metadata.	\N	{}	{"clinical trials","data collection","data reuse"}	{completion}	{}	{"IT infrastructure",standards}	{https://sphn-semantic-framework.readthedocs.io/en/latest/sphn_framework/sphn_metadata_catalog.html}	{}	{}	2025-11-14 12:53:19.259	2025-12-11 12:40:29.287	t	SPHN
